{
  "The largest part of the brain, making up about 80% of brain mass, is the:": "",
  "Hypothalamus": "",
  "Cerebellum": "",
  "Cerebrum": "",
  "Brainstem": "",
  "The cerebrum is the largest brain structure, comprising about 80% of total brain mass, and is responsible for higher-order functions including conscious thought, reasoning, voluntary movement, and sensory processing.": "",
  "The frontal lobe is primarily responsible for:": "",
  "Processing visual information": "",
  "Voluntary motor control, planning, decision-making, and personality": "",
  "Maintaining balance and coordination": "",
  "Processing auditory information": "",
  "The frontal lobe contains the primary motor cortex (precentral gyrus), the prefrontal cortex for executive functions, and Broca's area for speech production, making it essential for voluntary movement, planning, and personality expression.": "",
  "The visual cortex is located in the:": "",
  "Frontal lobe": "",
  "Temporal lobe": "",
  "Parietal lobe": "",
  "Occipital lobe": "",
  "The occipital lobe, located at the posterior part of the brain, houses the primary visual cortex (V1) and visual association areas that process all visual information received from the eyes via the optic nerves.": "",
  "The cerebellum coordinates:": "",
  "Hormone secretion and metabolism": "",
  "Emotional processing and fear responses": "",
  "Movement, balance, posture, and motor learning": "",
  "Conscious thought and memory formation": "",
  "The cerebellum, located posterior to the brainstem, fine-tunes motor output by comparing intended movements with actual movements, coordinating balance, posture, and smooth, precise voluntary movements.": "",
  "The medulla oblongata controls which vital functions?": "",
  "Visual and auditory processing": "",
  "Memory formation and consolidation": "",
  "Heart rate, breathing rate, and blood pressure": "",
  "Voluntary skeletal muscle movement": "",
  "The medulla oblongata is the most inferior part of the brainstem and contains vital autonomic centers that regulate heart rate, respiratory rhythm, blood pressure, and reflexes such as swallowing, coughing, and vomiting.": "",
  "The thalamus functions primarily as:": "",
  "A relay center for sensory information going to the cerebral cortex (except smell)": "",
  "The primary motor planning area": "",
  "The memory consolidation center": "",
  "The body's master hormone regulator": "",
  "The thalamus acts as the brain's central relay station, receiving sensory input from all senses except olfaction (smell) and routing it to the appropriate area of the cerebral cortex for conscious perception and processing.": "",
  "The hypothalamus regulates:": "",
  "Only hearing and balance processes within the inner ear and auditory cortex": "",
  "Only visual processing within the retina, optic nerve, and occipital cortex": "",
  "Homeostasis including body temperature, hunger, thirst, circadian rhythms, and hormone control via the pituitary": "",
  "Only voluntary skeletal movement coordinated through the motor cortex and cerebellum": "",
  "The hypothalamus is the master homeostatic regulator of the body, controlling body temperature, hunger, thirst, sleep-wake cycles, and the endocrine system through its connection to the pituitary gland.": "",
  "How many pairs of spinal nerves emerge from the spinal cord?": "",
  "24 pairs": "",
  "31 pairs": "",
  "12 pairs": "",
  "42 pairs": "",
  "There are 31 pairs of spinal nerves: 8 cervical, 12 thoracic, 5 lumbar, 5 sacral, and 1 coccygeal, each exiting through intervertebral foramina to serve specific body regions.": "",
  "The corpus callosum connects:": "",
  "The cerebrum and cerebellum": "",
  "The thalamus and hypothalamus": "",
  "The brain and spinal cord": "",
  "The left and right cerebral hemispheres": "",
  "The corpus callosum is the largest white matter commissure in the brain, consisting of approximately 200 million axon fibers that connect and allow communication between the left and right cerebral hemispheres.": "",
  "The three protective membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord are collectively called the:": "",
  "Ventricles": "",
  "Commissures": "",
  "Meninges": "",
  "Gyri": "",
  "The meninges are three protective membranes (dura mater, arachnoid mater, and pia mater) that envelop the brain and spinal cord, providing physical protection, support, and containing cerebrospinal fluid.": "",
  "What is the cerebral cortex?": "",
  "The white matter tracts deep within the cerebrum": "",
  "The thin outer layer of gray matter covering the cerebrum where higher-order processing occurs": "",
  "The protective bony covering of the brain": "",
  "The fluid-filled cavities inside the brain": "",
  "The cerebral cortex is the highly folded outer layer of gray matter (2-4 mm thick) covering the cerebral hemispheres, containing billions of neuron cell bodies responsible for consciousness, thought, language, memory, and voluntary movement.": "",
  "What is cerebrospinal fluid (CSF)?": "",
  "A thick, viscous lubricant found between the vertebrae": "",
  "A clear, colorless fluid that cushions the brain and spinal cord, removes waste, and maintains a stable chemical environment": "",
  "Blood that has been filtered to nourish the brain exclusively": "",
  "The fluid inside neuron cell bodies that contains organelles": "",
  "Cerebrospinal fluid is a clear fluid produced mainly by the choroid plexuses in the brain ventricles that circulates through the ventricles and subarachnoid space, cushioning the CNS, removing metabolic waste, and maintaining chemical homeostasis.": "",
  "What is Broca's area?": "",
  "A region in the occipital lobe responsible for visual processing": "",
  "A region in the cerebellum that coordinates balance": "",
  "A region typically in the left frontal lobe responsible for speech production and motor planning of speech": "",
  "A region in the brainstem that controls breathing rate": "",
  "Broca's area is located in the posterior part of the left frontal lobe (inferior frontal gyrus) and is responsible for speech production and language processing; damage leads to Broca's aphasia, where patients understand language but struggle to produce fluent speech.": "",
  "What is Wernicke's area?": "",
  "A region in the frontal lobe that controls voluntary movement": "",
  "A region in the brainstem involved in autonomic regulation": "",
  "A region typically in the left temporal-parietal junction responsible for language comprehension": "",
  "A region in the hypothalamus that regulates hunger": "",
  "Wernicke's area is located at the junction of the temporal and parietal lobes (usually left hemisphere) and is critical for understanding spoken and written language; damage results in fluent but nonsensical speech and impaired comprehension.": "",
  "What is the limbic system?": "",
  "The bony structures that protect the brain": "",
  "The network of blood vessels supplying the brain": "",
  "The motor pathways descending from the cortex to the spinal cord": "",
  "A group of interconnected brain structures (including the amygdala, hippocampus, and cingulate gyrus) involved in emotion, memory, and motivation": "",
  "The limbic system is a collection of deep brain structures including the amygdala (fear and emotion), hippocampus (memory formation), and cingulate gyrus that together regulate emotional responses, memory consolidation, and motivational behaviors.": "",
  "What is the hippocampus?": "",
  "A cerebellar structure that coordinates fine motor movements": "",
  "A limbic system structure in the temporal lobe essential for forming new declarative memories and spatial navigation": "",
  "A brainstem structure that regulates heart rate": "",
  "A cortical area in the frontal lobe responsible for speech": "",
  "The hippocampus is a seahorse-shaped structure in the medial temporal lobe that plays a critical role in converting short-term memories into long-term memories and in spatial navigation; bilateral damage results in the inability to form new declarative memories.": "",
  "What does 'meninges' refer to?": "",
  "The three protective connective tissue membranes (dura mater, arachnoid mater, pia mater) covering the brain and spinal cord": "",
  "The nerve fiber tracts connecting the two hemispheres": "",
  "The four fluid-filled chambers within the brain": "",
  "The folds and grooves on the surface of the cerebral cortex": "",
  "The meninges consist of three layers: the tough outermost dura mater, the web-like middle arachnoid mater, and the delicate innermost pia mater that adheres directly to the brain and spinal cord surface.": "",
  "What does 'somatosensory cortex' mean?": "",
  "The visual processing area in the occipital lobe": "",
  "The auditory processing center located in the temporal lobe": "",
  "The area of the brain that plans and executes voluntary movements": "",
  "The region of the parietal lobe (postcentral gyrus) that receives and processes touch, pain, temperature, and proprioceptive information from the body": "",
  "The somatosensory cortex, located on the postcentral gyrus of the parietal lobe, processes all bodily sensations including touch, pressure, pain, temperature, and proprioception, with a topographic map (sensory homunculus) representing different body parts.": "",
  "What is a ventricle in the context of the brain?": "",
  "A blood vessel that supplies the cortex": "",
  "A cavity within the brain that is filled with cerebrospinal fluid": "",
  "A fold on the surface of the cerebral cortex": "",
  "A type of neuron found only in the brainstem": "",
  "The brain contains four ventricles (two lateral, the third, and the fourth) that are interconnected fluid-filled cavities where CSF is produced by the choroid plexus and circulated to cushion and nourish the CNS.": "",
  "What does 'lateralization' mean in brain function?": "",
  "The crossing of nerve fibers from one side of the body to the opposite side of the brain": "",
  "The specialization of certain functions to one cerebral hemisphere over the other": "",
  "The progressive deterioration of brain tissue on one side": "",
  "The concept that both hemispheres perform identical functions simultaneously": "",
  "Lateralization refers to the tendency for certain cognitive functions to be more dominant in one hemisphere; for example, language is typically lateralized to the left hemisphere while spatial processing is often dominant in the right hemisphere.": "",
  "A 68-year-old man is brought to the emergency room with sudden-onset slurred speech, right-sided facial drooping, and weakness in his right arm. A CT scan reveals a blood clot in his left middle cerebral artery. Which type of stroke is this, and why does the left-sided blockage cause right-sided symptoms?": "",
  "Hemorrhagic stroke; bleeding compressed both hemispheres equally": "",
  "Hemorrhagic stroke; the right hemisphere controls the right side of the body": "",
  "Ischemic stroke; the clot traveled to the right side of the brain before lodging": "",
  "Ischemic stroke; motor nerve fibers cross (decussate) in the brainstem, so left brain damage causes right-sided deficits": "",
  "This is an ischemic stroke (caused by a clot blocking blood flow). Motor pathways decussate (cross over) at the medullary pyramids in the brainstem, so damage to the left motor cortex produces contralateral (right-sided) weakness and facial drooping.": "",
  "A patient with damage to Broca's area can understand everything said to them but speaks in broken, effortful phrases like 'want...water...please.' A different patient with damage to Wernicke's area speaks fluently but says nonsensical sentences and cannot understand questions. Which lobe houses each of these language areas?": "",
  "Broca's is in the frontal lobe (speech production); Wernicke's is in the temporal-parietal area (language comprehension)": "",
  "Both are located in the occipital lobe": "",
  "Broca's is in the parietal lobe; Wernicke's is in the cerebellum": "",
  "Broca's is in the temporal lobe; Wernicke's is in the frontal lobe": "",
  "Broca's area in the left frontal lobe controls motor speech production (damage causes non-fluent aphasia), while Wernicke's area at the left temporal-parietal junction handles language comprehension (damage causes fluent but meaningless speech with poor comprehension).": "",
  "A neurologist examines a patient who suffered a traumatic brain injury to the cerebellum. Which of the following deficits would you expect the physician to observe during the examination?": "",
  "Complete blindness in both eyes": "",
  "Inability to form new memories": "",
  "Uncoordinated, jerky movements, poor balance, and difficulty with precise motor tasks": "",
  "Complete loss of sensation on one side of the body": "",
  "Cerebellar damage results in ataxia (uncoordinated movement), dysmetria (inability to judge distances accurately), intention tremor, impaired balance, and difficulty with smooth, coordinated motor tasks like walking or touching the nose with a finger.": "",
  "A college student suffers a severe concussion in a car accident and afterward cannot remember events from the 30 minutes before the crash, nor can she form new memories for several days. Which brain structure is most likely affected, and which memory function has been disrupted?": "",
  "The occipital lobe; visual memory is disrupted": "",
  "The hippocampus; its role in consolidating short-term to long-term memory has been disrupted": "",
  "The cerebellum; procedural memory has been disrupted": "",
  "The medulla oblongata; autonomic memory centers are disrupted": "",
  "The hippocampus is essential for converting short-term memories into long-term memories; injury to this structure causes both retrograde amnesia (loss of recent pre-injury memories) and anterograde amnesia (inability to form new memories) until the structure recovers.": "",
  "A neurosurgeon is planning to remove a tumor located near the postcentral gyrus of the left parietal lobe. The patient is warned they might experience changes in sensation after surgery. What specific sensory function might be affected, and on which side of the body?": "",
  "Loss of smell on the left side": "",
  "Diminished touch, pain, and temperature sensation on the right side of the body": "",
  "Loss of hearing in the right ear": "",
  "Loss of vision in the left eye": "",
  "The postcentral gyrus is the primary somatosensory cortex, and because sensory pathways cross over (decussate), the left parietal cortex receives somatosensory input from the right side of the body, so surgery in this area could impair touch, pain, and temperature perception on the contralateral (right) side.": "",
  "A child is diagnosed with hydrocephalus, a condition in which cerebrospinal fluid accumulates excessively within the brain ventricles. If left untreated, what is the primary danger of this condition?": "",
  "The accumulating fluid increases intracranial pressure, compressing brain tissue and potentially causing brain damage": "",
  "The CSF will leak out of the skull through the ear canals": "",
  "The excess fluid will dissolve the myelin surrounding axons": "",
  "The excess CSF will cause neurons to fire uncontrollably, leading to seizures": "",
  "Hydrocephalus occurs when CSF drainage is blocked or absorption is impaired, causing fluid buildup in the ventricles that increases intracranial pressure, compresses delicate brain tissue, and can lead to permanent brain damage if not treated with a shunt to drain excess fluid.": "",
  "A patient is admitted to the hospital with meningitis. The physician explains that the infection has spread to the membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord. Which specific structures are inflamed, and what are the classic symptoms?": "",
  "The ventricles are inflamed, causing only dizziness and nausea": "",
  "The cerebral cortex is inflamed, causing seizures and paralysis": "",
  "The meninges (dura, arachnoid, and pia mater) are inflamed, causing severe headache, stiff neck, fever, and photophobia": "",
  "The cranial bones are infected, causing skull pain and swelling": "",
  "Meningitis is inflammation of the meninges (the protective membranes around the brain and spinal cord), presenting with the classic triad of severe headache, nuchal rigidity (stiff neck), and fever, often accompanied by photophobia and altered mental status.": "",
  "A physical therapist is working with a spinal cord injury patient who has lost all sensation and movement below the waist but retains full upper body function. The injury is most likely at which level of the spinal cord?": "",
  "Sacral region, which would only affect bladder function": "",
  "Cervical (neck) region, which would affect all four limbs": "",
  "Within the brain itself, not the spinal cord": "",
  "Thoracic (mid-back) region, which would result in paraplegia with preserved upper limb function": "",
  "A thoracic spinal cord injury results in paraplegia (loss of motor and sensory function in the lower extremities) while preserving upper limb function, since the nerves supplying the arms exit above the injury level from the cervical region.": "",
  "A researcher is studying a patient whose corpus callosum was surgically severed to treat severe epilepsy (split-brain patient). When an image is shown only to the patient's left visual field, the patient cannot verbally name the object. Why?": "",
  "The surgery damaged Broca's area directly": "",
  "The patient has lost all visual processing ability": "",
  "The left visual field is processed by the left hemisphere, which was damaged during surgery": "",
  "Left visual field information goes to the right hemisphere, which cannot communicate with the left hemisphere's language centers because the corpus callosum is severed": "",
  "In a split-brain patient, the left visual field is processed by the right hemisphere, but since the corpus callosum (the bridge between hemispheres) is severed, visual information cannot reach the left hemisphere where language centers (Broca's and Wernicke's areas) are located, making verbal naming impossible.": "",
  "A patient in the ICU has suffered severe damage to the medulla oblongata from a brainstem stroke. The medical team places the patient on a ventilator immediately. Why is damage to this specific brain region life-threatening?": "",
  "The medulla controls voluntary limb movements essential for survival": "",
  "The medulla is responsible for hormone production needed to maintain metabolism": "",
  "The medulla contains the vital centers for breathing, heart rate, and blood pressure regulation, so damage can cause respiratory and cardiac arrest": "",
  "The medulla controls memory, and without memories the patient cannot maintain consciousness": "",
  "The medulla oblongata houses the cardiac center, vasomotor center, and respiratory center that control heart rate, blood pressure, and breathing. Damage to these vital autonomic centers can result in cessation of breathing and cardiac function, making it immediately life-threatening.": ""
}